<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-186-078 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 721 969</DOCID><JOURNAL>CAD-CAM International  April 1991 v10 n4 pS30(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Designs on Mac. (computer-aided design use of Apple Macintoshmicrocomputer)(Case Study) (Apple Macintosh Cad Supplement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Trevett, Nicky.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Design consultancy Moggridge Associates finds Apple's Macintoshmicrocomputer a useful tool for producing sketches and modelmakingdrawings as part of its design process.andP;  Computer-aided design(CAD) software packages such as Intergraph Corp's Microstation andAshlar Inc's Vellum are powerful tools when combined with theMacintosh's friendly user interface.andP;  Sketches can be producedmuch faster on the computer than by hand.andP;  Modelmaking drawingsare then produced from those sketches.andP;  The drawings are accurateenough for use by the model shop, and engineering drawings canthen be made from the modeling drawings.andP;  In addition to CADsoftware, computer-aided manufacturing (CAM) programs help withproduction of models.andP;  CAM software can provide computer-basednumerical control for manufacturing.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ashlar Inc. (Products)Intergraph Corp. (Products)Apple Computer Inc. (Products)Moggridge Associates (Equipment and supplies).andO;Ticker:    INGR; AAPL.andO;Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (Usage)Vellum (CAD software) (Usage)MicroStation (CAD software) (Usage).andO;Topic:     Computer-Aided DesignGraphics SoftwareCase StudyDesign.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>